## Add scenario 3 — rules → data quality → reasoning → analysis → audit trail

Context: New live, gated journey that runs **after scenarios 1 and 2** and
reuses the durable ``test_scenario_1`` domain. It exercises the "governed
enrichment" loop on top of a built knowledge graph: generate data-quality
rules (SHACL) and business rules (SWRL / decision tables / SPARQL / aggregate),
run the data-quality rules on the knowledge graph, run the business rules and
materialise the inferred triples back into the graph, then run the graph
Analysis, interpret it with the graph-interpreter agent, and record the
interpreted result in the unified audit trail. Mapped each step to the real
internal API and honoured the lifecycle constraints discovered while reading
the code.

Key design decisions:
- Targets the highest **DRAFT** version (V2 after scenario 2), never the
  PUBLISHED V1: comments/tasks — the surface the audit trail is written through
  — are writable only in DRAFT/IN-REVIEW.
- A freshly branched version (scenario 2's ``create-version``) carries the
  ontology + mappings but has no graph data, so the scenario builds the KG once
  (and skips the costly rebuild on re-runs by checking ``/dtwin/sync/status``).
- Data-quality generation uses the deterministic
  ``GET /ontology/dataquality/suggest`` + ``accept-suggestions`` (no LLM);
  business-rule generation uses the async ``agent_business_rules_generator``.
- Data-quality runs against ``backend=graph``; reasoning enables every phase
  (tbox/swrl/graph/decision_tables/sparql_rules/aggregate_rules), then
  ``/dtwin/reasoning/materialize`` writes the inferred triples to the graph.
- Analysis = ``/dtwin/metrics/compute`` then ``/dtwin/metrics/interpret``.
- "Add the result to the audit trail": a plain comment is *not* recorded in the
  review audit log, but a task that anchors a comment appends a ``commented``
  row — so the scenario posts the full write-up as a comment, creates a task
  referencing it, and asserts the event surfaces in ``/domain/audit-trail``.

Changes:

1. tests/e2e/scenarios/test_scenario_3_rules_analysis.py (new)
   New scenario ``TestScenario3RulesAnalysis``. Gated by
   ``ONTOBRICKS_SCENARIO_LIVE=1`` + the ``scenario`` marker (auto-applied by
   the scenarios conftest). Skips with guidance when the domain is absent or has
   no DRAFT version (run scenarios 1 & 2 first). Idempotent: reuses an existing
   KG, only accepts new rule suggestions, and tolerates a run that infers
   nothing (materialise step becomes a no-op). Env-tunable timeouts for build /
   rule-gen / data-quality / reasoning / analysis.

Modified files:
- tests/e2e/scenarios/test_scenario_3_rules_analysis.py (new)

Tests: `uv run pytest -q -m "not scenario"` → 3003 passed, 58 failed, 17
skipped, 4 deselected in 271s. The new scenario is `scenario`-marked, so it is
deselected from the routine run; it collects cleanly (`--collect-only` → 1 item)
and the gate skips it without the env var (`1 skipped`). The 58 failures are the
pre-existing full-suite event-loop/test-isolation flakes in the API/MCP suites
(`RuntimeError: Runner.run() cannot be called from a running event loop`) —
confirmed unrelated by re-running the affected files in isolation/together
(e.g. `test_review_endpoints.py` + `test_comment_endpoints.py` → 16/16 passed).
The live journey itself was not executed (requires a running app + SQL
warehouse + LLM serving endpoint + scenarios 1 & 2 having run); run it with
`ONTOBRICKS_SCENARIO_LIVE=1 uv run pytest
tests/e2e/scenarios/test_scenario_3_rules_analysis.py -m scenario -v -s --no-cov`.


## Mapping Diagnostics — exclude relationships of excluded entities + row counts

Context: In Mapping Diagnostics a relationship pointing at an excluded entity
(e.g. `has: Meter → MeterReading` when `MeterReading` is excluded) was wrongly
reported as an "target entity not found" error. The relationship should follow
the entity and be treated as excluded too. Also added per-item row counts:
each Entity and Relationship now shows the number of rows returned by its source
query so users can spot empty/large sources at a glance.

Changes:

1. src/back/objects/mapping/Mapping.py
   - `run_diagnostics`: drop relationships whose source/target resolves to an
     excluded entity (new `_references_excluded_entity` helper), so they no
     longer surface as errors. Genuinely missing (non-excluded) entities still
     error as before.
   - Extracted `_index_entities_by_alias` from `_build_entity_lookup` so the
     same alias index can be built for excluded entities (Extract Method).
   - Replaced `_check_query_has_data` with `_probe_query_rows`, a single
     `COUNT(*)` round-trip returning both the data-presence check and the row
     count (no extra query). Entity/relationship results now carry `row_count`.
2. src/front/static/mapping/js/mapping-diagnostics.js
   - New `_countBadge` helper; render the row-count badge in entity and
     relationship headers.
3. src/front/static/mapping/css/mapping-diagnostics.css
   - Styles for `.diag-count-badge` (and `.diag-count-empty` for zero rows).
4. tests/units/mapping/test_mapping_service.py
   - New `TestProbeQueryRows`, `TestRunDiagnosticsExcludedEntityRelationships`,
     and `TestRunDiagnosticsRowCounts`.

Modified files:
- src/back/objects/mapping/Mapping.py
- src/front/static/mapping/js/mapping-diagnostics.js
- src/front/static/mapping/css/mapping-diagnostics.css
- tests/units/mapping/test_mapping_service.py

Tests: `uv run pytest -q tests/units/mapping/test_mapping_service.py` → 51 passed.
Full `uv run pytest -q -m "not scenario"` → 3013 passed, 58 failed (the same
pre-existing full-suite event-loop/test-isolation flakes documented above;
confirmed unrelated — the affected API files pass in isolation and alongside the
mapping tests, 64/64).


## Document `uv.lock` deploy guardrails in rules + deploy skill

Context: The Databricks Apps deploy runs `uv run --frozen` and installs verbatim
from `uv.lock`. Two recurring failure modes have broken deploys before: (1) the
lock's wheel URLs getting rewritten from the public CDN
(`files.pythonhosted.org`) to the internal proxy
(`pypi-proxy.dev.databricks.com`, which cold-caches fresh wheels and times out),
and (2) the lock drifting out of sync with `pyproject.toml`. The dev shell
defaults `UV_INDEX_URL`/`PIP_INDEX_URL` to the proxy, so any bare `uv lock` /
`uv sync` silently churns the lock to proxy URLs. Verified the current lock is
clean (3653 URLs, all `files.pythonhosted.org`, zero proxy; `uv lock --check`
against the public index → exit 0) and captured the checks/rules so the issue
can't recur.

Changes:

1. .cursor/09-package-management.mdc
   New "`uv.lock` is deployment-critical — DO NOT let it churn" section: the two
   failure modes, the day-to-day `--frozen` rule, the public-index re-lock
   command, the read-only pre-deploy verification commands (URL host check +
   `UV_INDEX_URL=https://pypi.org/simple uv lock --check`), and the
   `git checkout -- uv.lock` recovery for accidental churn.
2. .claude/skills/deploy/SKILL.md
   Added pre-flight step 5 (verify lock is on the public CDN and in sync via the
   public index) and two new "Don't" entries (no bare `uv lock`/`uv sync`; never
   commit proxy URLs).
3. .cursor/08-testing-and-deployment.mdc
   Cross-referenced the new lockfile section from the Deployment bullet.

Modified files:
- .cursor/09-package-management.mdc
- .claude/skills/deploy/SKILL.md
- .cursor/08-testing-and-deployment.mdc

Tests: not run — documentation/rules only, no Python touched. Verified the
documented commands against the live lock: `rg -c 'pypi-proxy\.dev\.databricks\.com' uv.lock`
→ no matches; `rg -o 'url = "https?://[^/"]+' uv.lock | sort -u` → only
`https://files.pythonhosted.org`; `UV_INDEX_URL=https://pypi.org/simple uv lock --check`
→ exit 0 (in sync).


